content:
It comes in two flavors - the daily planner has a page for every day of the year and includes suggested deep sky objects you can observe or image that night. It also has a summary list for each month.

The weekly planner is a little more lightweight and has the week spread out over two pages. It doesn't have daily deep sky objects, but does include the monthly summaries.

Lastly, of course, there's calendars, plus important regional and religious dates to help with planning your year.

content:
The NZ elections were super disappointing, but one bright spot for me was that a lovely gentleman who welcomed my partner and I in Dunedin when we were stranded has got into Parliament for the Greens.

He's 100% a no-BS, genuinely stand-up guy. NZ is very lucky to have him. Wish more US folks like this wouldn't get weeded out of our money-driven election ringer. https://scottwillis.nz/

content: Oct 17 EWE: #CO2 ‚Äî Carbon dioxide pollution expected to hit new record in 2023, researchers say. Global CO2 emissions should be falling by around five percent this year, said Glen Peters, research director at the CICERO climate research institute in Norway. Instead they have continued to rise, according to his research, with current expectations that the year will see emissions up between 0.5 percent and 1.5 percent. https://phys.org/news/2023-10-carbon-dioxide-pollution.html #ClimateCrisis

content:
I appreciate the Washington Post story from Michael Coren on how to replace a car with an e-bike, but it's still stuck in car-centric thinking.

https://www.washingtonpost.com/climate-environment/2023/10/17/electric-bikes-cars-cost-testing/

E-bikes are electric vehicles.

E-bikes are the most popular electric vehicles.

E-bikes are the most revolutionary electric vehicles.

E-bikes rarely get subsidized, unlike giant e-cars and trucks, because lawmakers think of them as toys, not vehicles.

E-bikes are electric vehicles.
